3815149A096B47E4A90285DFB26300A8.description: Participate in an activity that simulates the demands and responsibilities of parenting.

CD38960FC3C446DB85843DC70B658D86.description: Neglect: Failing to adequately provide for the child's safety, as well as physical and emotional needs. Children who are unsupervised also fall under the neglect category.

B0CCA1D6127F4B3F99B16688AF493991.description: Sexual: Any sexual contact with a child, inappropriate touching, fondling, exposure, or obscene language. Severe legal penalties will result.

672FF54CBE7E462EABF6401BA1A33B42.description: Emotional / Verbal: Deliberately injuring a child's self-concept and emotional wellbeing. This includes verbal attacks, threats, or humiliation.

BFDC8768641643F58AEB2B3D3B48244E.description: Physical: deliberately injuring a child by hitting, biting, kicking, burning, throwing objects or anything that basically hurts the child. Examples: shaken baby syndrome, fetal alcohol syndrome, drug addicted babies

08EEF9DE3E9C4819B47B88FCF7545BB9.description: Define and discuss child abuse as a result of teen parenting. (Types, factors that cause, sources of help for parents and/or children of abuse, ways to prevent).

F4B87A4BE25947E5876605D193FB426D.description: Marriage: having a relationship built on trust, fidelity, commitment (children make a strong relationship stronger, but a weak relationship weaker)

8BC951A640634FC3B126F3E5D6C01C76.description: Intellectual: understanding the principles and guidelines of child development throughout life

773EAF917EAF4FA2AAFDC64DF827C4BB.description: Emotional: keeping emotions under control in high-stress situations due to lack of sleep

7284980A73AF452CA1F0F0B141BF4021.description: Moral: teaching values, responsibility, choices, and consequences

DF5C996CD7FE458B92AA6671A3A54CC4.description: Financial: able to provide the necessary items to raise a child

1F2B43A1893D43AE846507C6DA05F730.description: Social: give up personal free time and activities to put baby's needs first

81CF8CE16FD6457694D8F31FAA8DEB4C.description: Physical: have good overall health and ability to carry a child full term

D152D4046ED7410F956A0223E31A179B.description: Discuss the various demands of parenting and the impact on families, careers and communities. (physical, social, financial, moral, emotional, intellectual, marriage)

DE11043B6E64407FB21B1C4029802057.description: Abstinence: the deliberate decision to avoid harmful behaviors, including sexual activity before marriage and the use of tobacco, alcohol, drugs or other harmful activities. Abstinence is the best way to prevent exposure to an STI.

5D5F257E49C04581BC23BA8E94D49253.description: Define abstinence and discuss how abstinence before marriage strengthens marital bonds.

7655AA30FAB44C66BF0A6B956E3E1192.description: Consequences/Problems Associated with Early Physical Intimacy: unwanted pregnancy, risk of contracting STIs, breaking up before marriage, divorce and adultery risks are higher, guilt, fear and other emotional distress, weaker marital bonds, could be against the law

6379D2DC73EB4C5BA486A87115FE45DF.description: Define and discuss emotional related consequences of early physical intimacy. (STI's, abstinence, pregnancy, emotional distress, adoption, abortion, etc.)

30496E44D03B418E99B1012B7E0988E7.description: Consequences of contracting an STI: some are incurable, some cause cancer, some cause complications that affect the ability to reproduce, some can be passed from an infected female to her child before, during or after birth

356C3D21875B461EA9B759FFB27DB016.description: Parasitic: can be cured if caught early enough (pubic lice)

DC45728AADA249DD9D301466E9818691.description: Viral: have no cure, but are controllable with medications (HIV/AIDS, genital herpes, hepatitis, HPV/genital warts)

6DA4AE217F0E465198BE9882C5CEC6C3.description: Bacterial: can be cured if caught early enough (Gonorrhea, syphilis, chlamydia, Pelvic Inflammatory Disease-PID (bacterial complication of STI infections) )

5B70FE90AD6A4CCF96502B6E738FB251.description: STI: Sexually Transmitted Infection capable of being spread from person to person through sexual intercourse, oral, anal, genital or digital contact. Can also be spread through IV drug use/blood to blood contact. There are three categories of STI's:

53993D17542347AAB213A69F3062582C.description: Define and discuss STI and other health related consequences of early physical intimacy.

8342C785AC644AFD9130F938C37FC3D6.description: Discuss the progression to physical intimacy.

27BD0311CB0E4054B7AB2EEFA7801471.description: Discuss why young adults are not ready for the demands and responsibilities associated with parenthood and the consequences of early physical intimacy.

498D5E53ED514794A83931055F6EE2C9.description: Actively participate in an experience involving the practice of appropriate social interactions in the family, career and / or community setting.

60EB069DA711414A86B24172AB8857F2.description: Skills for Career Success: communication skills (listening, speaking and writing), teamwork, critical thinking (solve problems and make decisions), initiative / sel-motivation, productive and positive attitude, leaderships skills, adaptability, time management, integrity / honesty, dependability, interpersonal skills ("people" skills)

146756A9780D48829E40A672274E27CB.description: Skills for School Success: manage time wisely and productively, create good study habits, set attainable goals often, concentrate and ask questions, learn how to be a good note-taker, complete your assignments and turn them in on time, get organized, be motivated to learn, work hard (no excuses), do your best and be committed

B1378E2300824A4CAA71940DCF6D9562.description: Compare and contrast characteristics of social interactions/etiquette in different social settings.

3D7DB62109F44774966EC869EF2AED43.description: Basic Social Skills: be polite, say "please" and "thank you", make eye contact when talking, hold the door for others, turn your phone off when appropriate, keep conversations polite and appropriate, be punctual (on time), use appropriate language

D508BB9FCAF240EA9539D15552115646.description: People will remember you by your behavior, whether good or bad.

3C59EB9CA97042F4A77767C90C439CF7.description: Using good manners and appropriate social skills shows respect for the people and places around you.

32DAB228CDFF4F3DAAB684FF86E7ABF3.description: Identify appropriate social interaction techniques in the family, career and community settings. (Phone calls, thank you notes, table manners, tipping, cell phone etiquette, etc.). *STEM (Behavioral Science/Technology)

E2054966CD934FF6A6F2F529351F3149.description: Analyze the importance of appropriate social interactions in relation to families, careers and communities.

D0A2461C20F84854B720978C470139CA.description: Dealing with Sexual Harassment: let the person know that you are uncomfortable with their behavior. Tell them to stop and be assertive. Tell someone you trust: parent, relative, coach, teacher, counselor, etc. Keep a record of the harassment to show what's been happening. If you see or suspect something, say something.

279840FC0DD84301A9431089B1153D45.description: Examples of Sexual Harassment: name calling, threats, inappropriate jokes, spreading rumors, gestures, leers, writing on bathroom walls, grabbing, pushing, cornering, unwanted kissing/touching, inappropriately touching body

9C1B4C65C04D439293F388E4E6A8D48A.description: Sexual Harassment: any unwanted conduct or communication of a sexual nature that negatively affect a person's relationships, employment opportunities or environment. Harassment may be verbal or physical.

F80257790430442091F3BA664E77EB08.description: Define sexual harassment and develop assertive behavior skills as a means of protection from sexual harassment and abusive situations.

96E6DF796B1A445DB6879F33CD32FFC1.description: Analyze personal rights that apply to dating (The right to: be yourself, an enjoyable safe date, have your values respected, care for and protect your body, establish and protect your reputation, be free from guilt and fear, say no).

9BDC2B986A0F454CAC6EE3987E4778D8.description: Infatuation: Starts and burns out quickly, material love, jealousy, based on physical attraction, stubbornness leading to many arguments, insecurity and doubt about relationship, rush into physical intimacy before ready, taking/ focused on "me", self-centered

B25DCCE5C4D743A8BEF4E24424876B93.description: Love: slowly built, security and trust, strong friendship, long-lasting, love the entire person, want the other person to grow, willing to compromise, ability and desire to wait for physical intimacy, giving/ focused on "you", dual commitment, self-less

F7780B8C39DE4A569D79F3AAC0AE34FE.description: Explain the difference between infatuation and love.

ACBD50B4370B4D738EF4719891344F86.description: Discuss reasons and motives for dating.

A872E09ABDA34808B2B98C69DF716FA4.description: Teens who are in or suspect someone they know is in an abusive relationships should tell someone (parents, friends, trusted adult, teacher, counselor, police, professional mental health worker, etc.)

3E198F18CDB54CEC92EF098C2FAFEDE2.description: Why Teen Stay In Abusive Relationships: embarrassed or ashamed, afraid violence will escalate if they try to end the relationship, convinced it's their fault, no experience with healthy dating relationships, confuse jealousy with love, ignore reality (don't know their being abused), afraid friends and family won't believe them, feel like there is no one they can turn to for support, mix of "good times" and hope that partner will change, believe that being involved with someone is the MOST important thing in their life (better to be with someone than alone)

8C0821FC9DB54891B7D22DC9018F52E7.description: Relationship Red Flags: wants to get serious quickly, will not take NO for an answer, is overly jealous and possessive, wants to choose their partners friends and activities, is controlling and bossy (makes all the decisions), puts partner down when alone and in front of others, makes partner feel guilty ("If you really loved me you would..."), blames the victim for behavior ("It's your fault I get so angry"), apologies for violent behavior ("I'll never do it again, I promise."), has strong ideas about gender roles

564D177B13474D48AB02F377FB557110.description: Dating Violence: a pattern of behavior to establish power and control over another person through fear and intimidation. Often including the threat or use of violence. It occurs when one person believes they are entitled to control another person and those involved are in an intimate or close relationship.

69EDC2A92B8A41408F61C22998C1050F.description: Emotional/Psychological: mental violence that can include constant verbal threats and abuse, harassment, excessive possessiveness, isolating abused person from others, damage of personal property, intimidation, etc.

701DC81F172546718A37D20F06488957.description: Sexual: any non-consensual, forced sexual behavior. It may escalate to rape or sexual assault.

6A5251F07E9F466FAB79719F9B3C4587.description: Physical: can begin with threats of violence, punching fist through wall, escalates to pushing, slapping, restraining, etc. Finally, it can become life threatening.

E36F8E10271D400B9D248EF557302D5A.description: Define and discuss dating violence and how to report and/or deal with those situations appropriately.

81340C9C4276478EB0BE70B7E5784499.description: How to deal: Realize what happened and why, accept your anger/ pain and move on, keep your distance, think through everything, talk to friends and family, write your feelings down, clean personal space, keep fond memories, don't overreact, find happiness in other areas of your life, stay active, let it go and move forward

04F56EEA1F004EE6AE0602C1B0B75BBA.description: How to end: pick an appropriate place, choose the right time, do it in person, be honest but sensitive, keep your emotions under control, use "I" Messages

944126652A7D4F11B81B068F93F0711D.description: Discuss appropriate ways to end a relationship and how to deal with a relationship that has ended.

55B5A7EE86BC426D8019644299C51DFD.description: Disadvantages of Early Paired Dating: relationships accelerate more rapidly, more pressure to entertain partner, might be awkward getting to know them, more expensive, early physical intimacy

CD6DA752DEC74A69BE17495EED275E96.description: Discuss the problems and consequences of early pairing.

1323B0EFB65C4F5FAF7A2339D3DB5D39.description: Advantages of Group Socialization/Dating: safety in numbers, relaxed fun, meet new people, easier to communicate, less opportunity for early physical intimacy

8D9A0A557FD9437285FCAFE6FDC28F18.description: Discuss advantages of group socialization rather than paired dating at an early age.

C63E5AD6D0284FC8B9E04AB2E652DA0E.description: Getting acquainted, friendships, phone calls/texting, socializing with groups, group dating, double dating, and pairing/single dating

C38BDC431923478998C4ED46A401A36D.description: Identify and understand the progression/ avenues of adolescent attractions. Explore the ways relationships begin, develop and grow.

3FD80EFDAE8844969A6956D30423397C.description: Discuss how dating relationships begin and develop.

77D250B6D099415D898D36DA753FFAA0.description: Students will understand the importance and impact of healthy opposite gender relationships in families, careers and communities.

8F6206E392F34C44BA3E3D2F70C91F0D.description: Practice using two appropriate refusal skills in each of the following environments: family, career and community.

A59D8FE518794403858360751C2049B0.description: Explore various types of refusal skills (stay calm, make eye contact, be assertive, repeat if necessary, walk away).

0D40ECE0B30A4F4A8D37F35EDE1ED752.description: Impact of social media on career opportunities: social rejection, bullying, gossiping, sexual harassment and abuse, etc.

1F20D5DA621E455F91A83AD55CAA1495.description: Behaviors that help Fight Additions: exercise, sports, music, service, hobbies, learning, family, faith, friends, journal writing

9C479D96227441B097EA5DAB314F7340.description: Do it Now: It will only get harder the longer you wait.

DAEC01EB1FFD426192C7C31B6B6FB85A.description: Get Help: you are much better off it you don't battle an addiction alone. Some great sources of help are parents, good friends, support groups counselors and teachers

C161F3629DCB4D3C890A4F120DD58988.description: Admit it: recognize that you have a problem

E3F8052A3339438591B2B96B7DD31A04.description: Realities of Addition: Addictions can become stronger than you. Addictions are not just about you. Addictions destroy dream and future opportunities. Addictions can cloud judgment, affect memory, change taste buds, inhibit perception, slow bodily functions/reaction time

D267743359DF4DF891E69DCFF66ADB67.description: You want to escape from your current problems

86705240AEE94E1F97F7B63D001BBF50.description: You feel confined and want to rebel

D5EE599B4A364647946B1121D449E1EE.description: You are trying to hide pain from the past (death, divorce, abuse, etc.)

46B3F38F0B3E487DA4070A484485D5D2.description: Your friends are doing it and you feel pressured by them

A05A7E9C344941DDB3795B0576A90F6C.description: You feel insecure and desperately want to belong

311E5290255C4B9DB5AC4E0BB7A5BD5A.description: Group associations can provide: gives self-esteem, reduces stress, offers opportunities for social and leadership skills, understands social expectations, provides identity and emotional security, satisfies a sense of belonging and unity

74F085720BE6459AA612A7E25B534438.description: Being rejected: others prefer not to be with you, when you try to join in but are shut out

731B68365C7748F8B8C467D24C3E7ED6.description: Being alone: choosing to be alone, positive time for self, being along doesn't mean someone feels rejected or lonely

B5677837D28C49C3A21C60BCE22D0267.description: Feeling lonely: not feeling like you are part of a group (large or small), feels left out or overlooked altogether when they really want to eel included in the group

AB4FD1E686FE488BA6F19061E9262D72.description: Positive and negative effects of group associations in the community (Explain the difference between feeling lonely, being alone and being rejected.)

67D9CF67592E404AA48DEF21E93D4703.description: Negative: doing something just to fit in, loss of self-control, personal conflict, judged by actions of the group, etc.

2F83A1A85E934B908E9B9EE75F00B9E1.description: Positive: pressure into doing good things, influences you to stick to values/goals, helps you listen to your feelings, help others by setting a good example, etc.

39E29F0E201A44F8BD367D7B42D2FA81.description: Positive and negative effects of peer pressure

9B6CCE80D0CD43CD93A779DA64DF6D2E.description: How a group might positively or negatively influence a young adults life

8CE939FA22D84C5AB0499F721CB325D3.description: Explore the impact of group associations in the present and future in regards to families, careers and communities. *STEM (Biology/Science/Behavioral Sciences)

F7B0FE6DE6E24DCAA9D45819CF94782B.description: Examine skills for developing and maintaining friendships.

B8E52809D8214501AEE30BD3F52017B1.description: Negative Friendship Characteristics ("Toxic" Friends): unsupportive, take/take/take, stifling, give nothing back, unreliable, overly demanding, talks behind friends back, always turns the conversation to them and their problems, your positives are their negatives, uses sarcasm ("Just Kidding...", "No offense, but...")

47E142D45DC04E48B9B5E9D6E4D02522.description: Positive Friendship Characteristics: listen to each other (use active listening), don't put each other down or hurt each other's feelings, try to understand each other's feelings and moods, help each other solve problems, give each other compliments, disagree without hurting each other, are dependable, respect each other, are trustworthy, give each other room for change, care about each other

820D7F32A2E54E7790570811193773A2.description: Discuss positive and negative characteristics of friendships.

9E6E875D52B54C4F88BD0329906E2887.description: Social Interest: someone to go places with

6D4A9E69955A4BB2992168D45AD6B8E5.description: Empathy: someone to care about you

6162F52568FB4866A6D5217B675A5A0A.description: Feedback: someone to help analyze what your situations and feelings are

CAFCD538DDB443DBBE0D6C9875B4BA42.description: Disclosure: someone to talk to and confide in

B9C52AE1FE734272B7E2EECD7D2EE3AF.description: Identify personal needs for friendship and a positive social network.

56C8CF41E1CB4C0F8BA0E305C561BB9D.description: Intimate: Friends you have had for a long period of time, deep sharing of emotions/ experiences

98B5FDAFC9714FCEA1215CA779B56D4A.description: Close: Friends you hang out with and share some emotions/ personal experiences with

4890E590DD324A11897E296D62DE7122.description: Casual: People you share a common interest with like school and activities

2942A1F6CBBE48329596EA27BDFE5D30.description: Acquaintance: People you recognize but don't really know

52E41CB704154D61B05FD611CB30CF48.description: Identify the different types of friendship.

954FD80B48D0474DAC1AA43FCA0BE245.description: Differentiate between peers and friends and identify types of friendships (acquaintances, casual, close, and intimate).

96FA3396A97F479CACF974EE8F6FE358.description: Students will investigate the present and future impact peers/friends have on individuals, families, careers and communities.

4CC41335025746268D3E8E42EA28B377.description: Reflect on the role and impact of personal attitudes and behaviors on family relationships.

B4A43674023448F3BBD1E85809539EE6.description: Analyze how behaviors and choices during teenage years directly affect future health and well-being in the personal aging process. *STEM (Science)

40F0CDE2BBD84BB1B99C5FF3A39DC4BD.description: Both at crossroads in life, anxieties about the future, hormonal changes, drug use/abuse, suffer from loneliness and depression, preoccupied with driving, concerned about their independence, victims of discrimination, prime candidates for abuse and criminal activity, face disapproval of any marriage plans, don't have much money, etc.

BE2FA3B822F74CFBA097F39048D69EFF.description: Identify ways in which teens and seniors/elderly can develop closer and more meaningful relationships by recognizing similarities.

5FDED233F9D04CE59143A9615BBCDF6B.description: Identify ways in which teens can build trust to develop closer and more meaningful relationships with parents/guardians.

564EE8912B8D402D934204E52D681D8C.description: Birth Order: the order in which a child is born into a family. (Oldest Child, Middle Child, Youngest Child, Only Child). It can have an impact on personality and development.

B31E8270C5BA45FB9E7C3960A931CF33.description: Discuss birth order theory and analyze how it may influence sibling relationships.

C378D5CC8DC64F6AB4034C80154FE705.description: Discuss how relationships with parents, siblings and the elderly affect families, careers and communities. Explore methods of building relationships of trust and respect with parents/guardians.

AA9096F13F1A4412B2856F8190EAC1FC.description: Identify how young adults can help meet the basic needs of others in the family including parents, siblings and the elderly.

EF633F94DACC4BF289DD6292FF7AB7F4.description: Physical needs must be met before any others can be achieved.

436635BA42E540AD81611A277C29EC18.description: Pyramid (begins at the base): physical needs, safety needs, love and belonging needs, esteem needs, and self-actualization (achieving personal goals).

A2910879BC004A52835FF81FE5C238A3.description: Understand how Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs is consistent throughout the life span.

6D19694F5C184E1394CC7D85F101248F.description: Discuss the connections between increased freedoms, responsibilities, rights and privileges (more freedom requires more responsibility).

7C4E0F46A43040558A5FC66B0AEBAB8A.description: Destroy: withdrawal from family, avoid certain family members, destructive communication, withhold affection and emotions

701CDC6C3C1E44F7A7364AC58D6BF145.description: Strengthen: appreciation, affection, commitment, time together/ build traditions, creative problem solving, constructive communication

0A91488BA82742A5B9156D39400F79A8.description: Identify ways teenagers can strengthen or destroy family relationships.

94EAAD9C699341E0A40AE8B32CD666FB.description: Explain how a young adult's attitudes and behaviors affect family relationships.

0C44E4019F10424F9A6761B68A278DF9.description: Students will connect the impact of family relationships and the role teenagers have in the family.

98E3F3EF9B1E4AA3B63DCFA72ADBDEE1.description: Conduct career research and pathway planning for a career of choice based upon selfassessment results. (Career Investigation FCCLA STAR Event could be integrated.)

E643009E2F934BF594F4F17CBAE324D9.description: Discuss skills critical for entering the world of work: dress/grooming, positive attitude, work ethic, responsibility, dependability, integrity, adaptability, communication, teamwork, and basic interviewing skills.

4E949514253945B39693EF56022334E6.description: Complete a career related personality self-assessment to understand how personal values and attitudes influence career choices.

E7E046AC8232414BB056B34D2E76B469.description: Explore various career pathways and identify a career pathway based upon personality traits.

11B411B22B7B4C3EB61A8524A1654E20.description: FCS Educator, Employment Counselor, Marriage and Family Therapist, Social Worker, Counseling/ Psychologist, Community Service Director, Geriatric Service Worker, Vocational Rehabilitation Counselor, Adult Day Care Center Coordinator (Refer to Utah CTE College & Career Pathways)

3734D6CAFAD843B0BEBBB71693753FFD.description: Introduce Family, Human Services and Education careers.

C20276844DA44948A3B56F5E0958A201.description: Identify how career choices will affect future success in families, careers and communities. *STEM (All STEM Areas)

55E68709C0A74106AE4F0DDDFFEC3C8B.description: Critique qualities exhibited as a personal role model for others.

8E3BCBEDC6D443CA8EC6B5E084E25943.description: Individuals, especially teens, should be careful who they select as their personal role models

34110DF2F6CB41AD9A11A513384B8CBE.description: Role Model: a person who models patterns of behavior, attitudes and values (can be both positive or negative)

4975C28EFD6D427DAEAE0208A9DD681F.description: Define the term "role model" and evaluate the qualities of positive role models in one's own life.

BE380B9EFB614DF1B57F3054C282338F.description: Negative effects: exaggerated sexuality, increased aggressiveness, increased violence and criminal activity, unrealistic expectations, increased deception, etc.

EE6B5D19DA3B45898C6960AEEF110C53.description: Positive effects: instant information world-wide, spreads knowledge, educates people on basic rights, skill development, informed advertisements, educational programming, etc.

040A98E5E3A0423881B2C6A9EA3B8526.description: Analyze the positive and negative messages of media and the influences on personal attitudes and behaviors.

B5232F656EC8486B822986B2227D2077.description: Understand and analyze the influence of media in families, careers and communities. *STEM (Technology)

CE6F6C5978224F1B8AE2EC39CB83DE72.description: Identify situations in families, careers and communities for applying the critical thinking process in managing and preventing problems.

B8F6DB87CC0145839907C63805493AAD.description: Take a position based on logic (make a decision)

53720FD99ED344998BEC8F1A2292CDAD.description: Identify personal and family values that conflict with the situation

C6C6D4EC6AF742D09A8AA362BB04512D.description: Identify the components of the critical thinking process in order:

DF542DF5B27C49C5A274B19C09577CF0.description: Describe and practice critical thinking skills crucial in problem solving. *STEM (Engineering /Creativity & Problem Solving)

29444A2F311A46B68C7456B5329C10A1.description: Demonstrate the correct usage of I-Messages in each of the following environments: family, career and community.

B747A5730293480486946112A3830C6D.description: Active Listening Skills: pay attention, look at the speaker and make eye contact, stop other tasks and listen, listen with appropriate body language, give verbal clues that show you are listening, don't interrupt, don't shift your attention to your own problems, don't let your emotions get in the way, don't rush the conversation, put the phone away

04D07F4A3CAF42F7B314DA5E85AAB2A1.description: Positive Conflict Resolution Skills: try to stay positive and calm, be aware of your emotional triggers, use active listening skills to understand, focus on cooperation instead of winning, ask questions, use appropriate body language/nonverbal communication, use "I" Messages, be specific about what is bothering you

3E6A90A20D9C4747838DFB0482F87FD9.description: Problem-Solving: this style shows a willingness to compromise to solve the problem positively. Characterized by: using collaboration to solve the problem, win-win attitude, two-way communication, used "I" Messages

EE353FB03C6344328892152D429DCD2A.description: Confrontation: this style is aggressive and sometimes hostile. Characterized by: "My way or the highway" thinking, very confrontational and competitive, used to gain power and control, uses "You" Messages, can damage relationships

8690B468020D4B7A99C7485DD7DA8CE6.description: Avoidance: this style tries to avoid the problem all together rather than face it. Characterized by: changing the subject, "giving in" to avoid confrontation, avoiding the issue in hopes it will go away, communicating through the "grapevine"

5B48DAD5C52943B49E1ADF335EE26175.description: Identify how positive conflict resolution and active listening skills enhance human relationships.

76FB067BE5C24F88864D8A5227B4F858.description: "I" Messages are a helpful way of communicating how you feel and why you feel that way without losing control of your emotions. They allow you to resolve conflicts without others feeling blaed or attached. They do take time and practice to use effectively.

878324F2522A43E794C5E78ED37BF3D0.description: Utilize I-Messages in developing positive relationships in families, careers and communities.

32C96B5E10AA48FD8E3229D1ADC7435B.description: Nonverbal Communication: the way a person expresses themselves through movement, posture and facial expression. It can often be misread and misunderstood. It is possible to send one type of verbal message and a different type of non-verbal message at the same time.

5A4D5894F3CF44098D26288CE37ADB2B.description: Examples: insults, harassment, teasing, threatening, lying, accusing, using "You" Messages, swearing, sarcasm, gossip, topping / "one upping", not listening

7747B2DC7C414D9BACC44DA1FC5AE187.description: Destructive Communication: negative communication that "tears down" yourself and others.

F5113B32AD8A47E0963BF30A40EA2B64.description: Examples: Giving positive and encouraging messages, sending clear messages, keeping the confidences (appropriate secrets) of others, using tact (saying something sensitive without hurting or offending), using "I" Messages, asking questions, being honest and open, speaking with respect, using active listening skills.

4EA51A95E8BD4634A7C1D9905FAEA8A1.description: Constructive Communication: positive communication that contributes to a meaningful exchange of ideas and builds up yourself and others.

260E99C87DA04943802BCE48C817FEAE.description: Identify and analyze the three types of communication (constructive, destructive and nonverbal).

A9079448E59240B6BF1437B1B410CE61.description: Open two-way communication, all take responsibility for comments/actions, all remain calm and control strong emotions, respect for each other's feelings, all have a "win-win" attitude.

8FB4496A32E046D79C7A912A346EA22B.description: Adult-like: highest level of communication and the most effective. It takes time to learn and use. Involves active listening.

2F4E049548EA4540A2C3C53D9AE1507A.description: Giving instructions, directing, not listening, demanding, ordering, punishing.

C3E41B1765FA4352B804857C78E2BAF5.description: Parent-like: nothing to do with actually being a parent (two year olds are pro.) Tries to direct others behavior. Only effective because it usually gets someone else to comply or give in.

13053BC874464F40B12848DC174EBB68.description: Self-Centered, no listening, whining, name calling, giving orders, interrupting, acting out of control, yelling, throwing tantrums, topping / "One Upping"

63BF7E6E22AE4D1FA8F7BCD162905B8F.description: Child-like: the easiest and most natural communication to use. Very immature method and the least effective when you are an adult.

51AC7C8161A84799BD000108C116C1E0.description: Discuss styles of communication and their effects (child-like, parent-like, adult-like).

4A57E49C7DAC40CA824049FE9FF63271.description: Identify and recognize personal communication styles and discuss the importance of quality communication skills as they relate to family, career and community environments.

1F108B76A1134B07A1A697929BBEEC48.description: Stress Management Techniques: acknowledge it, good diet, regular sleep, exercise, building good relationships, get organized, make a "to-do" list, don't procrastinate, mentally count down, take a break, laugh, say "no" to things, listen to music, etc.

A3B6E3D6CCC54A9AB2470A9396F7DD14.description: Identify and review stress management skills (causes and effects, management techniques).

EB28E8372D7A40B48A83813785D81251.description: Stress Reducer: anything that helps individuals to reduce or relieve stress. (Ex: acknowledge it, good diet, regular sleep, exercise, building good relationships, etc.)

A36D2160EBE84679BBF6C68C96B168C2.description: Stressor: things or events that cause us stress (Ex: school, family, friends, work, others)

0556D9BEFF574B819DB81B4788054213.description: Distress: Bad or negative stress (Ex: death in the family, divorce injury, etc.)

CCE04E3D673745E68E28C349FF6C3E43.description: Eustress: Good or positive stress (Ex: weddings, special date, birth of a baby, etc.)

CA71F6AA59D74CE2B1A330CF132DF364.description: Behavior: acting-out, inability to eat, extreme anger, hitting/punching, nail biting, nervous twitch, etc.

3FE156B5A8DE49AEB751410BE90BE1CB.description: Emotional: worrying, irritability, crying, feeling anxious, nightmares, depression, etc.

3EBBE3A766BB4C75B5A6982AB37F9EFD.description: Physical: tiredness, injury, insomnia, headache, tense muscles, etc.

29C17330DCD44553B27BBA80951FDD42.description: Stress: the body's reaction to pressure, either mentally or physically

DA894ADD8982486BB4E751A1B6AC6394.description: Define stress (stressor, eustress, distress, stress reducer). *STEM (Biology)

8C2D1D8673764CCD9C5E0DBF0DEB22DE.description: Financial: Dollar costs to individuals and communities as a result of behavior

3743F50435C54438A7D83532BD3B7120.description: Physical: Harm or injury that can come to people because of the behavior

0FEB2911422240B9ABB118BC76226E95.description: Ethical: Moral and religious values that are violated because of behavior

80BA419DC6E8469AAA427732C9608F63.description: Social: Effects on the community, family, and individuals because of the behavior

10A883188C2B4197BAFBACCA5AC38447.description: Mental: Those factors that affect an individual emotionally because of the behavior

7DB2ED317BBD4A54A24CC8EAD5C43AA9.description: Legal: The results in choosing behaviors that are against the law

40A5A5CE021541F98A1B27E4F4C247F7.description: Identify the consequences of controlled and uncontrolled emotions on individuals, families and communities.

F650140F6A1E4F29A647D82BBE9F36F2.description: Assertive Behavior: calmly but insistently state their feelings in a non-emotional way, do not allow others to manipulate, intimidate or control their behavior, they use "I" Messages, if in a threatening situation they will walk away and seek help is appropriate, they tell someone if the situation is harmful, dangerous or against the law.

2E2E9639DB5B4406A0F6B08DB0756603.description: Aggressive Behavior: individuals that are always looking for a fight, whether or not it is their business they are right in the middle of it, masters at verbal or physical battle, thrive on intimidating others, believe that aggression breeds aggression, often brings out the worst in others.

0B9E6EBC4E754841A556A7575967BC65.description: Passive Behavior: people who let others walk all over them, they follow the "crowd" and allow others to make decisions for them, they lack the courage to express inner feelings, they are followers, they allow passivism to control their emotions and are disappointed in how they are manipulated by others, they see something wrong, but do nothing about it.

7357C0761AC745C1BE7AD1A57EC20B9B.description: Analyze differences between passive, assertive and aggressive behavior.

B5E0EAF644604A3AA63ABAC264A41898.description: Expressing anger in a healthy way: walk away from the situation until you have control of your emotions, recognize and accept the emotion, try to pinpoint the exact reasons why you feel angry, problem solve strategies for dealing with the situation in advance, do something physical like exercise or playing a sport, seek help if needed.

700CBC21DA9C4029AEFC48DE98C15A3E.description: Physical effects of uncontrolled anger: Headache, digestion problems, insomnia, anxiety, depression, high blood pressure, skin problems like eczema, heart attack/stroke

58667E4035DC4D6EB85BB4EB7080B49D.description: Uncontrolled anger can lead to arguments, physical fights, abuse, assault and self-harm. On the other hand, well-managed anger can be a useful emotion that motivates you to make positive changes.

20B02052139B492AA5AEF637A794565B.description: One of the hardest emotions to control or express positively is anger.

0198ED80F218404D81B178397B37BF96.description: Compare positive and negative methods of expressing and communicating emotions in family, career and community environments.

2F5584A459E14DEB8EADD8BA5C8E7A99.description: Discuss and analyze the healthy expression of personal and professional emotions.

31CBDAAB300441B28F2AF591C4CC7CE6.description: Create a road map of life that analyzes the influence of personal values and goals related to college/career pathways.

2E5C63DFD1C2444EB8AB4DE25D5CCE60.description: Successful goals are realistic, measurable and specific.

69A5D95352274D75B19DA7F0076EF531.description: Short-term goals help individuals achieve long-term goals.

366189790D4F49F4ABF32D113A19A1F2.description: Long-Term Goals: usually takes longer to accomplish (Months-Years)

D28D3651ABD941C1A3C705B424D859ED.description: Short-Term Goals: usually accomplished quickly (1-3 days)

F0D2EF489DA94FCAA2586267E0BFB76F.description: Goals: plans you make to help you reach or accomplish something in the future.

5F37AB682A7043DCB6C015AFAB8FB035.description: Define short and long-term goals. Discuss how short term goals are the stepping stones to achieving long term goals. Discuss qualities of successful goals.

8A6CC063C1A74F5EA39BC33D3CCAD2F5.description: Results of acting against values: feeling guilty, being ashamed, legal problems, lose trust, lose self-esteem, unhappiness, lowering values to justify actions

D7291E7A5A5542ED84B9B4244987CA3E.description: Results of acting within values: have a clear conscience, be self- reliant, peace of mind, gain trust, build self- esteem, happiness and contentment.

0A854093168A4DFA924EB89347730B0E.description: Intangible values: non-material things that usually can't be bought with money (Ex: love, honesty, kindness, etc.)

E25B0AC06FDA4E509B3B590A8B0356DE.description: Tangible values: material things in our lives that usually cost money to obtain (Ex: jewelry, cars, clothes, etc.)

8C42A70BA43B4FC28EDBA67F2229B772.description: Values: anything in life that is important to us. They determine how we live and how we tell the difference between right and wrong.

76DBB74839E34D69ADBE7763A2D03064.description: Identify and define personal values (tangible and intangible) using the values cycle.

6FDF20DED81A4150A2004AB19771D77F.description: Ways to build self-concept include: accept yourself, forgive yourself, learn a new skill, reach out to others, be positive, be assertive, make a new friend, improve a friendship, do something nice for someone, recognize your strong points, don't compare yourself to others, set and accomplish goals, give yourself credit for your positive qualities, live within your values system, care about other people, positive self-talk.

7E9DA94853E7429AA2E9F9D32F909E55.description: Self-image: the way we see ourselves physically

664FE9B9054C4CB7972AED8D11AD62FC.description: Self-esteem: the way we think or feel about ourselves (changes from moment to moment). Two types: High self-esteem and low self-esteem

37A672D606A24360B932C9E9C704D984.description: Self-confidence: believing in yourself and your abilities, trusting yourself to do what is right no matter what

EF2838A7B04146388708F51D2D7AE9EC.description: Self-concept: combination of self-esteem and self-image

E03E585E74DC4D9D8BCF2A8FDE97712B.description: Identify skills which lead to an understanding of self (self-esteem, self-concept/self-confidence, how to build self-concept/self-confidence, and personality assessment).

931A768CF5FB40C2BA3644B72B86A48C.description: Specific roadblocks: crisis level trauma, substance abuse, divorce, abuse, teen pregnancy, OCD, addictions, etc.

85C2616F4F2242A3A2F0E0B74CB12E6F.description: Developmental Tasks: Develop mature relations with peers of both genders, Adopt a socially approved gender role, Accept your body as it is and make the most of the body you have, Become emotionally independent from parents and other adults, Prepare for marriage and family life, Select and prepare for a career, Adopt priorities in keeping with personal goals and societal expectations, Adopt socially responsible behavior.

BBFF5A9512664CE0A48D3EB6D8914780.description: Identify Havighurst's developmental tasks and challenges that occur during the teenage years and conditions that can impede, delay, or interrupt these tasks\roadblocks.

CB460FEED07846A8BFB5B283FD0AE670.description: Discuss how each person is unique, but alike in Havighurst developmental stages. *STEM (Human Development/Biology)

F7DA9ADADFE54315BB33CE179F036294.description: The class will complete FCCLA Step One. http://www.uen.org/cte/facs_cabinet/facs_cabinet10.shtml

74388AB60DA3495DAD5076A46F8E6208.description: Students will gain skills to help them deal with young adult transitions into adult life and college/career success.
